@Cindy 

Did you mean to say that PICK AND ROLL doesn’t meet Sam Corbin’s description of an “irreversible binomial”? It’s not that ROLL AND PICK just “sounds wrong,” it’s that as you correctly say, the pick has to come first. 

One of the few compliments I ever got while playing sports was a “Nice pick!” during a pickup game in college. I’d never seen my teammate before and as far as I know never saw him again (it was a big campus).

@Hardroch 

Glad you enjoyed it. 

I thought of you last night when I noticed that the comment system had me back in Austin. It was weird; I’d already made a few comments from Durango before it sent me back to Texas.

@Cindy 

I consider myself to have a very good sense of direction (well beyond the Manhattan grid), but I can hardly wrap my head around those street names, and I fear I'd get hopelessly lost-! Your description is hilarious! ☺️

And I'd always thought Queens was bad... Inevitably there is a Drive circling through an intersecting Street and Ave, all identified by numbers -- and residence addresses include numbers related to the street they're on. (Clearly I know very little about this adjacent borough! I never had much reason to drive there back in the pre-smartphone days, but once I did, I immediately bought a spiralbound Hagstrom 5-Boro street map. Lifesaver!)

@Amy 

I wanna know at what point in my life I went from “I can’t wait until the next Highlights/Mad/Boys’ Life*/Rolling Stone gets here” to “Oh, boy — another Texas Bar Journal/Sierra Club magazine to put on the coffee table and recycle in a month.”

*I just learned that Boys’ Life is now Scout Life, which isn’t surprising.

